    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4473442159" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4473442159" />
    <a title="Michael Bellesiles" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/110818334-michael-bellesiles"><img alt="Michael Bellesiles" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1586272368p2/110818334.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4473442159?book_show_action=true">Jan 13, 2022</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michael Bellesiles" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michael Bellesiles" href="/user/show/110818334-michael-bellesiles">Michael Bellesiles</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780805075700" href="/book/show/7863.Set_The_Night_On_Fire">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4473442159" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17560926472011262353">“New York City was not the origin and center of everything” [6]. We need to be reminded of that obvious fact a bit more often, as east-coast historians have too often set the agenda for the profession. Mike Davis and Jon Wiener should help dispel that illusion, at least for the last-half of the twentieth century. Repeatedly in the 1960s, Los Angeles was at the cutting edge of important progressive movements. <br/><br/>Set the Night on Fire is a fabulous and fascinating work of history. I must admit to a s</span>
  <span id="freeText17560926472011262353" style="display:none">“New York City was not the origin and center of everything” [6]. We need to be reminded of that obvious fact a bit more often, as east-coast historians have too often set the agenda for the profession. Mike Davis and Jon Wiener should help dispel that illusion, at least for the last-half of the twentieth century. Repeatedly in the 1960s, Los Angeles was at the cutting edge of important progressive movements. <br /><br />Set the Night on Fire is a fabulous and fascinating work of history. I must admit to a special appreciation for this book, which is in many ways the context of my childhood. At times it was unnerving how well I recall the events and people who fill these pages. The key events and people are all covered, giving a vivid sense of Los Angeles in the 1960s and early 1970s. The authors correctly highlight the tyrannical triumvirate of the authoritarian police chief William Parker, the vile Mayor Sam Yorty, and the hypocritical reactionary Cardinal McIntyre. But the real villains of the book (and of my childhood) were the members of the violent and racist organization known as the LAPD. Working with the FBI, the LA police department targeted any organization dedicated to equal rights, attacking and infiltrating every significant organization on the left, working to create divisions while undermining if not eliminating anyone who showed promise as an organizer and leader. They also beat the crap out of anyone they felt like, with special attention given to blacks, Hispanics, and the young. If nothing else, they were busy, committing more acts of violence than any other group in the 1960s.<br /><br />This is a rich study of the people of one of America’s great cities struggling to move forward against the reactionary resistance of entrenched political and economic forces. The book covers an enormous amount of territory in fascinating detail, from Sister Mary Corita to La Raza, from Budd Schulberg’s Inner City Cultural Center (where I saw my first play) to the Black Panthers, from murderous cops to heroic religious leaders standing up for human rights. The book addresses every major social movement of the long 1960s (i.e. 1959-1972), with attention to the areas where they worked together for positive social change. The book’s first section alone is worth the read; the authors do an outstanding job setting the stage for the Watts uprising in 1965 and craft an honest and forceful study of those events while showing the ways that the media worked with the LAPD to craft a counter-narrative of violent hoodlums seeking to spread anarchy. In my humble opinion, the book could have been a bit more intersectional, especially in regards to the women’s movement, but the work’s thoroughness kept me turning the pages at a rapid pace. I was most impressed with their study of the key role played in the movements for social change by the city’s high school students—a level of activism by teenagers which may be unmatched in American history. This is one of the finest works of history I have read in the past several years and I highly recommend it. Davis and Wiener make evident the reality of John Kennedy’s prediction, “Those who make peaceful revolution impossible make violent revolution inevitable” [609].<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="17560926472011262353" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

